/**
 * Book 4 Generator: Part ONE (Ch 1-4) and Part TWO (Ch 5-9)
 * NO EM DASHES.
 */

function ch01() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 1</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Data Cleaning: Why Raw Data Is Never Ready to Analyse</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Explain why data cleaning is an essential precursor to any analysis<br>• Identify common errors and anomalies in raw datasets<br>• Apply systematic techniques to clean and validate quantitative data<br>• Handle missing data appropriately without compromising integrity<br>• Document the data cleaning process for transparency and reproducibility</blockquote><h2>1.1 The Myth of Ready Data</h2>
<p>There is a persistent myth among novice researchers that once data collection is complete, analysis can begin immediately. This is almost never true. Raw data, whether gathered from surveys, sensors, experiments, or databases, is inherently messy. It contains errors, omissions, inconsistencies, and outliers that, if left unaddressed, will compromise any subsequent analysis. The process of transforming raw data into a form suitable for analysis is known as data cleaning, or data wrangling. It is often the most time-consuming phase of the research process, yet it is rarely discussed in detail in methodology textbooks (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>Data cleaning is not merely a technical exercise; it is a methodological necessity. If you feed incorrect data into statistical software, the software will still produce results, but those results will be meaningless. This is encapsulated in the well-known computing principle: "Garbage In, Garbage Out" (GIGO). The integrity of your findings depends entirely on the integrity of your data. Therefore, data cleaning is the first and most critical step in data analysis (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>The objective of data cleaning is not to alter the data to fit a hypothesis, but to ensure that the data accurately reflect the reality they are intended to measure. This requires a systematic approach, careful documentation, and a deep understanding of the variables and their expected values (Hair et al., 2019).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 300" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE DATA CLEANING PIPELINE</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="70" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Raw Data</text><text x="70" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Messy, errors</text><text x="135" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="150" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="200" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Screening</text><text x="200" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Identify issues</text><text x="265" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="100" height="60" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="330" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Cleaning</text><text x="330" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Fix or remove</text><text x="395" y="88" fill="#999" font-size="14">&#8594;</text><rect x="410" y="55" width="110" height="60" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="465" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="600">Clean Data</text><text x="465" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="8">Ready to analyse</text><rect x="150" y="150" width="240" height="60" rx="8" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="170" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="9" font-weight="700">COMMON ISSUES TO ADDRESS</text><text x="270" y="185" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="8.5">Out of range values (e.g., Age = 999)</text><text x="270" y="200" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="8.5">Missing data, duplicates, inconsistencies</text><line x1="200" y1="115" x2="200" y2="150" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="330" y1="115" x2="330" y2="150" stroke="#999" stroke-width="1.5"/><text x="270" y="260" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="10" font-weight="700">DOCUMENT EVERYTHING</text><text x="270" y="275" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Maintain a "cleaning log" for reproducibility.</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 1.1 Data cleaning is a systematic pipeline bridging raw collection and final analysis.</p></div>

<h2>1.2 Identifying Common Data Errors</h2>
<p>The first step in data cleaning is screening the data to identify anomalies. These anomalies typically fall into several categories. <strong>Out-of-range values</strong> occur when a response falls outside the logical boundaries of a variable. For example, if a survey asks for age and a respondent enters "999", or if a 5-point Likert scale contains a value of "7", these are clearly errors. They often result from data entry mistakes or participants misunderstanding the instructions (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p><strong>Inconsistencies</strong> occur when two variables contradict each other. For example, a participant might indicate their age as 18 but state they have been working professionally for 20 years. <strong>Duplicates</strong> arise when the same participant is recorded multiple times, which can happen in online surveys if a respondent refreshes the page or submits the form twice. <strong>Outliers</strong> are values that, while technically possible, are so far from the rest of the data that they distort the analysis. For example, in a study of income, one billionaire in a sample of middle-class workers is an outlier (Field, 2018).</p>

<h2>1.3 Handling Missing Data</h2>
<p>Missing data is one of the most pervasive challenges in quantitative research. Respondents skip questions, sensors fail, and records are lost. How you handle missing data can significantly impact your results. The worst approach is to ignore it, as statistical software will often default to dropping any case with a missing value (listwise deletion), which can drastically reduce your sample size and introduce bias if the data are not missing completely at random (Hair et al., 2019).</p>
<p>There are several strategies for handling missing data. <strong>Deletion</strong> involves removing cases (participants) or variables with excessive missing data. This is acceptable if the missingness is minimal and random. <strong>Imputation</strong> involves estimating the missing value based on other available data. Simple imputation methods use the mean or median of the variable, but these reduce variance and can distort relationships. Advanced methods, such as multiple imputation, use statistical models to estimate missing values more accurately. The choice of method depends on the amount of missing data and the mechanism causing it (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>
<p>Regardless of the method chosen, transparency is crucial. You must report how much data was missing, identify any patterns in the missingness, state how you handled it, and justify that decision. A clean dataset is not one that has been secretly altered; it is one that has been systematically and transparently prepared for rigorous analysis (Pallant, 2020).</p>`;
}

function ch02() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 2</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Coding and Categorising Data for Analysis</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Explain the purpose of coding in both quantitative and qualitative research<br>• Create and apply a codebook for quantitative variables<br>• Transform string variables into numeric codes for statistical software<br>• Understand the basics of qualitative coding and categorisation<br>• Recognise the importance of inter-coder reliability</blockquote><h2>2.1 What Is Data Coding?</h2>
<p>Data coding is the process of translating raw data into a format that can be analysed. In quantitative research, this usually means converting textual responses (such as "Male" or "Strongly Agree") into numerical values (such as "1" or "5") because statistical software requires numbers to perform calculations. In qualitative research, coding means assigning labels or tags to segments of text, images, or observations to capture their meaning and facilitate thematic analysis. Though the mechanics differ, the underlying purpose is the same: to organise and categorise data so that patterns can emerge (Saldaña, 2021).</p>
<p>Coding is a critical bridge between data collection and analysis. If data is coded incorrectly or inconsistently, the resulting analysis will be flawed. Therefore, coding must be systematic, documented, and, where possible, verified for reliability. It is not a mechanical task to be rushed, but an analytical task that requires careful attention to detail (Creswell and Creswell, 2018).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Quantitative vs. Qualitative Coding</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Quantitative Coding</h4><p><strong>Goal:</strong> Text to numbers<br><strong>Process:</strong> Pre-defined rules<br><strong>Output:</strong> Numerical matrix<br><strong>Example:</strong> "Yes" = 1, "No" = 0<br><strong>Tool:</strong> Codebook</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Qualitative Coding</h4><p><strong>Goal:</strong> Text to meaning<br><strong>Process:</strong> Emergent labels<br><strong>Output:</strong> Categories, themes<br><strong>Example:</strong> "I felt rushed" = [Time Pressure]<br><strong>Tool:</strong> Coding framework</p></div></div></div>

<h2>2.2 Quantitative Coding and the Codebook</h2>
<p>In quantitative research, every variable must have a clear numerical representation. For categorical variables, these numbers are arbitrary labels. For example, you might code "Urban" as 1, "Suburban" as 2, and "Rural" as 3. The numbers do not imply that Rural is three times greater than Urban; they are merely identifiers. For ordinal variables, the numbers represent rank order (e.g., a Likert scale from 1 to 5). For continuous variables, the numbers represent actual quantities (e.g., age in years) (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>The essential tool for quantitative coding is the <strong>codebook</strong>. A codebook is a master document that defines every variable in your dataset. It typically includes the variable name (a short, software-friendly label, like "EduLevel"), the variable label (a longer description, like "Highest level of education completed"), the values and their corresponding codes (e.g., 1=High School, 2=Bachelor's, 3=Master's), and the code used for missing data (e.g., 999). The codebook is the definitive reference guide for your dataset, ensuring that anyone looking at the numbers can understand what they represent (Hair et al., 2019).</p>

<h2>2.3 Qualitative Coding and Categorisation</h2>
<p>In qualitative research, coding is fundamentally different. Instead of converting text to numbers, the researcher assigns descriptive or interpretive labels to segments of data (interview transcripts, field notes, documents). These codes capture the essence of what is being expressed in that specific segment. Qualitative coding is usually an iterative process. In the first cycle (open coding), the researcher reads through the data and generates a large number of initial codes. In subsequent cycles (axial or focused coding), these initial codes are grouped into broader categories or themes based on patterns and relationships (Saldaña, 2021).</p>
<p>For example, if an interview participant says, "I never know what's expected of me until my boss yells at me," a researcher might apply the code [Role Ambiguity] or [Poor Communication]. As more data is analysed, the researcher might notice that [Role Ambiguity], [Lack of Feedback], and [Shifting Priorities] all cluster together under a broader category called "Unclear Expectations" (Charmaz, 2014).</p>

<h2>2.4 Ensuring Reliability</h2>
<p>Whether coding quantitatively or qualitatively, reliability is crucial. <strong>Inter-coder reliability</strong> (or inter-rater reliability) assesses the degree to which different researchers apply codes consistently to the same data. If two researchers reading the same survey responses or interview transcripts apply entirely different codes, the coding scheme is unreliable. This is typically addressed by having multiple researchers code a subset of the data independently, comparing their results, resolving discrepancies through discussion, and refining the coding rules before applying them to the rest of the dataset (Bryman, 2016).</p>`;
}

function ch03() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 3</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Choosing the Right Analysis Method for Your Data Type</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Distinguish between nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio data levels<br>• Explain how data type determines the appropriate statistical analysis<br>• Match research questions to the correct analytical techniques<br>• Understand the difference between parametric and non-parametric tests<br>• Use a decision tree to select the appropriate statistical test</blockquote><h2>3.1 The Dictatorship of Data Types</h2>
<p>One of the most common mistakes in quantitative analysis is applying the wrong statistical test to a dataset. This usually happens when researchers choose a test based on what they know how to do, rather than what their data require. The fundamental rule of quantitative analysis is that the type of data dictates the type of analysis. You cannot calculate a meaningful mean for nominal data (e.g., eye colour), and you lose valuable information if you reduce ratio data (e.g., exact income) to broad categories. Understanding data types is the prerequisite for choosing the right analysis (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>In statistics, variables are classified into four levels of measurement, often remembered by the acronym NOIR: Nominal, Ordinal, Interval, and Ratio. These levels are hierarchical; each higher level possesses all the characteristics of the lower levels, plus additional properties that permit more sophisticated analysis (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 340" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">LEVELS OF MEASUREMENT (N.O.I.R.)</text><rect x="60" y="60" width="420" height="55" rx="6" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="140" y="82" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">NOMINAL</text><text x="140" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Categories only</text><text x="320" y="82" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9.5">No order, no distance, no true zero</text><text x="320" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9">Examples: Gender, Religion, Eye Colour</text><rect x="60" y="125" width="420" height="55" rx="6" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="140" y="147" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">ORDINAL</text><text x="140" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Categories + Order</text><text x="320" y="147" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9.5">Ranked, but distances between ranks unequal</text><text x="320" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9">Examples: Class rank, Likert scales (often treated as interval)</text><rect x="60" y="190" width="420" height="55" rx="6" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="140" y="212" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="11" font-weight="700">INTERVAL</text><text x="140" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Order + Equal Distance</text><text x="320" y="212" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9.5">Equal intervals, but no true absolute zero</text><text x="320" y="230" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9">Examples: Temperature (Celsius/Fahrenheit), IQ scores</text><rect x="60" y="255" width="420" height="55" rx="6" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="140" y="277" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="11" font-weight="700">RATIO</text><text x="140" y="295" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">Order + Distance + Zero</text><text x="320" y="277" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9.5">Meaningful absolute zero allows ratio statements</text><text x="320" y="295" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.7)" font-size="9">Examples: Height, Weight, Income, Age</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 3.1 The four levels of measurement dictate which mathematical operations and statistical tests are permissible.</p></div>

<h2>3.2 Matching Questions to Tests</h2>
<p>Once you know the level of measurement for your variables, you must align them with your research question to select the correct test. Research questions generally fall into two broad categories: looking for differences between groups, or looking for relationships between variables. </p>
<p>If you are looking for <strong>differences between groups</strong> (e.g., "Do men and women differ in their salary?"), your independent variable is categorical (nominal or ordinal) and your dependent variable determines the test. If the dependent variable is continuous (interval or ratio), you might use an Independent t-test (for two groups) or ANOVA (for three or more groups). If the dependent variable is categorical, you would use a Chi-Square test (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>If you are looking for <strong>relationships between variables</strong> (e.g., "Is age related to salary?"), and both variables are continuous, you would use Pearson Correlation or Linear Regression. If both variables are ordinal, you would use Spearman's Rank Correlation. Choosing the right test is a process of elimination based on these parameters (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>

<h2>3.3 Parametric vs. Non-Parametric Tests</h2>
<p>A final consideration is whether your data meet the assumptions required for standard statistical tests. <strong>Parametric tests</strong> (like t-tests, ANOVA, and Pearson correlation) are powerful but require certain assumptions to be met, primarily that the data are normally distributed (the classic bell curve) and that variances are equal. They are typically used with interval or ratio data (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>If your data violate these assumptions (for example, if the data is heavily skewed or the sample is very small), or if your data is ordinal or nominal, you must use <strong>non-parametric tests</strong>. These are "distribution-free" tests that do not assume a normal distribution. For every major parametric test, there is a non-parametric equivalent: the Mann-Whitney U test substitutes for the Independent t-test, the Kruskal-Wallis test substitutes for ANOVA, and Spearman's rho substitutes for Pearson correlation. They are slightly less powerful, meaning they are less likely to detect a true effect, but they are safer when assumptions are violated (Field, 2018).</p>`;
}

function ch04() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 4</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Research Software Overview: SPSS, STATA, NVivo, Atlas.ti, R</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Understand the role of software in both quantitative and qualitative research<br>• Compare the features, strengths, and learning curves of major statistical software packages<br>• Understand the purpose of Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA) software<br>• Select the appropriate software tool for your specific research needs and skill level<br>• Recognise that software facilitates analysis but does not replace analytical thinking</blockquote><h2>4.1 The Role of Software in Research</h2>
<p>Modern research is inextricably linked to software. The days of calculating statistics by hand or physically cutting and pasting interview transcripts are long gone. Software tools allow researchers to manage massive datasets, perform complex calculations in milliseconds, and organise qualitative data with unprecedented efficiency. However, a common trap for novice researchers is believing that the software does the analysis. It does not. Software is merely a tool that executes the instructions it is given. It will happily calculate a mean for nominal data or perform a t-test on violated assumptions if you instruct it to. The researcher must provide the analytical thinking; the software only provides the processing power (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The choice of software depends on your research approach (quantitative vs. qualitative), your discipline's norms, your budget, and your technical proficiency. This chapter provides an overview of the industry standards.</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Software Selection Matrix</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-2"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Quantitative Software</h4><p><strong>SPSS:</strong> User-friendly, point-and-click, standard in social sciences.<br><strong>STATA:</strong> Code-based, powerful, standard in economics/epidemiology.<br><strong>R / Python:</strong> Open-source, infinitely flexible, steep learning curve.</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Qualitative Software (CAQDAS)</h4><p><strong>NVivo:</strong> Feature-rich, standard in academia, excellent for multimedia.<br><strong>Atlas.ti:</strong> Strong visual mapping, intuitive interface, robust coding.<br><strong>MAXQDA:</strong> Excellent mixed-methods integration, user-friendly.</p></div></div></div>

<h2>4.2 Quantitative Software: SPSS, STATA, and R</h2>
<p><strong>SPSS (Statistical Package for the Social Sciences)</strong>, now owned by IBM, is arguably the most widely used statistical software in the social sciences, psychology, and education. Its primary advantage is its graphical user interface (GUI). Users can perform complex analyses using point-and-click menus without needing to write code. This makes it highly accessible for beginners. However, it is expensive, and its point-and-click nature can sometimes make it difficult to document and reproduce exactly what steps were taken (though it does have a syntax language for this purpose) (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p><strong>STATA</strong> is highly popular in economics, political science, and epidemiology. It offers a blend of point-and-click menus and command-line syntax. Most advanced users interact with STATA via syntax (writing code scripts), which makes analysis highly reproducible: you can run a script months later and get the exact same results. It is faster than SPSS for large datasets and excels at panel data and econometric models (Acock, 2018).</p>
<p><strong>R</strong> is an open-source programming language and software environment for statistical computing and graphics. It is completely free and incredibly powerful, supported by a massive global community that constantly creates new packages for cutting-edge analyses. The downside is its steep learning curve: there are no point-and-click menus; you must learn to code. However, for those willing to invest the time, R offers unmatched flexibility and data visualisation capabilities (Field, Miles, and Field, 2012).</p>

<h2>4.3 Qualitative Software: NVivo and Atlas.ti</h2>
<p>Computer-Assisted Qualitative Data Analysis Software (CAQDAS) is fundamentally different from statistical software. CAQDAS does not analyse data for you; it cannot read an interview and tell you what the themes are. Instead, it provides a sophisticated digital workspace to help you organise, code, search, and visualise unstructured data like text, audio, video, and images (Silver and Lewins, 2014).</p>
<p><strong>NVivo</strong> is one of the market leaders. It excels at handling a wide variety of data types, including social media feeds and web pages. It allows researchers to create hierarchical coding nodes, link memos to specific data points, and run complex queries (e.g., "show me everything coded as 'stress' by female participants under 30"). It is particularly strong for large literature reviews and team-based coding (Bazeley and Jackson, 2013).</p>
<p><strong>Atlas.ti</strong> is the other major player in the CAQDAS space. It is renowned for its intuitive interface and its robust network mapping capabilities, which allow researchers to visually link codes, quotes, and memos to build conceptual models. It is highly favoured by grounded theorists and researchers who rely on visualising relationships between concepts (Friese, 2019).</p>
<p>Ultimately, the best software is the one that fits your workflow, your budget, and the norms of your specific academic department or research group.</p>`;
}

function ch05() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 5</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Descriptive Statistics: Summarising What Your Data Says</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Differentiate between descriptive and inferential statistics<br>• Calculate and interpret measures of central tendency (mean, median, mode)<br>• Calculate and interpret measures of dispersion (range, variance, standard deviation)<br>• Identify skewness and kurtosis in data distributions<br>• Present descriptive statistics appropriately in text and tables</blockquote><h2>5.1 The Purpose of Descriptive Statistics</h2>
<p>When you first import your raw, cleaned data into statistical software, you are typically faced with a matrix of hundreds or thousands of numbers. In this raw form, the data is incomprehensible. The primary purpose of descriptive statistics is to summarise and describe this mass of data in a meaningful, manageable way. Descriptive statistics tell you what is going on in your specific sample. They do not allow you to make conclusions beyond the people or objects you actually measured; that is the job of inferential statistics. But before you can infer, you must describe (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>Descriptive statistics are used to profile your sample (e.g., average age, gender breakdown), check for normality and outliers, and answer descriptive research questions. They form the first part of the results section in almost every quantitative paper. There are two main categories of descriptive statistics: measures of central tendency and measures of dispersion (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 280" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">TWO PILLARS OF DESCRIPTIVE STATISTICS</text><rect x="30" y="55" width="230" height="200" rx="8" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="145" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">CENTRAL TENDENCY</text><line x1="50" y1="90" x2="240" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="145" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">Where is the "middle" of the data?</text><rect x="60" y="135" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="145" y="152" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">MEAN (Arithmetic Average)</text><rect x="60" y="165" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="145" y="182" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">MEDIAN (Middle Value)</text><rect x="60" y="195" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="145" y="212" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">MODE (Most Frequent)</text><text x="145" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Describes the typical score</text><rect x="280" y="55" width="230" height="200" rx="8" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="395" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">DISPERSION (SPREAD)</text><line x1="300" y1="90" x2="490" y2="90" stroke="rgba(255,255,255,0.3)" stroke-width="1"/><text x="395" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9.5">How spread out is the data?</text><rect x="310" y="135" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#cf6a4f"/><text x="395" y="152" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">RANGE (Highest - Lowest)</text><rect x="310" y="165" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#cf6a4f"/><text x="395" y="182" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">VARIANCE (Avg squared deviation)</text><rect x="310" y="195" width="170" height="25" rx="4" fill="#cf6a4f"/><text x="395" y="212" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="9">STANDARD DEVIATION (Root of var.)</text><text x="395" y="240" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Describes the variability of scores</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 5.1 A complete summary requires both central tendency (the typical score) and dispersion (how scores vary around the typical score).</p></div>

<h2>5.2 Measures of Central Tendency</h2>
<p>Measures of central tendency attempt to identify the single value that is most typical or representative of the entire dataset. The <strong>Mean</strong> is the arithmetic average, calculated by adding all scores and dividing by the number of scores. It is the most commonly used measure for continuous data, but it is highly sensitive to outliers. A single billionaire in a room of average earners will pull the mean income to a level that represents no one in the room (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The <strong>Median</strong> is the exact middle value when all scores are arranged in order from lowest to highest. It is the 50th percentile. The median is resistant to outliers, making it the better measure of central tendency when data is skewed (as income data almost always is). The <strong>Mode</strong> is the most frequently occurring value in the dataset. It is the only measure of central tendency that can be used for nominal (categorical) data, where you simply want to know which category was most common (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<h2>5.3 Measures of Dispersion</h2>
<p>Central tendency only tells half the story. If Group A and Group B both have a mean age of 25, they might seem identical. But if Group A consists of 24- and 26-year-olds, while Group B consists of 10- and 40-year-olds, the groups are fundamentally different. Measures of dispersion tell you how spread out the data is around the centre (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The <strong>Range</strong> is the simplest measure, calculated by subtracting the lowest score from the highest. However, it only uses two data points and is extremely vulnerable to outliers. The <strong>Variance</strong> calculates the average squared distance of each score from the mean. While mathematically important, it is difficult to interpret because it is in squared units. The <strong>Standard Deviation (SD)</strong> is the square root of the variance, which brings the metric back to the original units of measurement. A small SD indicates that most scores are clustered tightly around the mean; a large SD indicates that scores are widely spread out. Reporting the Mean without the Standard Deviation is bad practice; they must always travel together (Hair et al., 2019).</p>

<h2>5.4 The Shape of the Data</h2>
<p>Descriptive statistics also involve examining the shape of the data distribution. A <strong>Normal Distribution</strong> is symmetrical and bell-shaped, where the mean, median, and mode are all the same value. Many statistical tests require data to be roughly normal. <strong>Skewness</strong> measures the symmetry of the distribution. A positive skew means a long tail pointing to higher values (e.g., income); a negative skew means a long tail pointing to lower values (e.g., scores on a very easy exam). <strong>Kurtosis</strong> measures the "peakedness" or flatness of the distribution. Checking these shapes visually via histograms and mathematically via descriptive statistics is a crucial step before applying advanced tests (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>`;
}

function ch06() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 6</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Inferential Statistics: Making Claims Beyond Your Sample</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Explain the fundamental difference between a sample and a population<br>• Understand the logic of inferential statistics and probability<br>• Define statistical significance and interpret a p-value correctly<br>• Differentiate between Type I and Type II errors<br>• Understand why effect sizes and confidence intervals are essential companions to p-values</blockquote><h2>6.1 From Sample to Population</h2>
<p>While descriptive statistics tell you what is happening in the specific group of people you measured (your sample), researchers usually want to make claims about a much larger group of people (the population). If you test a new teaching method on 100 students and their scores improve, your real question is not "Did these 100 students improve?" (descriptive statistics can answer that). Your real question is "If I applied this method to all students, would they improve?" This leap from the known sample to the unknown population is the domain of <strong>inferential statistics</strong> (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>Because you only measured a sample, you can never be 100% certain that the patterns you found are true for the whole population. There is always the possibility that your sample was weird-that by sheer random chance, you happened to select 100 students who were going to improve anyway. Inferential statistics use the laws of probability to estimate how likely it is that the results found in your sample reflect a true reality in the population, rather than just random sampling error (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 280" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">THE LOGIC OF INFERENCE</text><rect x="50" y="60" width="160" height="160" rx="80" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="130" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="11" font-weight="700">POPULATION</text><text x="130" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.85)" font-size="9">(Unknown Truth)</text><rect x="330" y="85" width="110" height="110" rx="55" fill="#c9a227"/><text x="385" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10" font-weight="700">SAMPLE</text><text x="385" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.9)" font-size="8">(Measured Data)</text><path d="M 190 90 Q 260 50 340 90" fill="none" stroke="#2d6a4f" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="5,5"/><polygon points="335,85 345,95 335,95" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="260" y="65" text-anchor="middle" fill="#2d6a4f" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Sampling Process (Random)</text><path d="M 330 190 Q 260 230 190 190" fill="none" stroke="#8b3a3a" stroke-width="2"/><polygon points="195,195 185,185 195,185" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="260" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b3a3a" font-size="9" font-weight="600">Statistical Inference</text><rect x="90" y="250" width="360" height="30" rx="6" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><text x="270" y="268" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="9">Inference estimates the probability that sample results represent the population.</text></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 6.1 Inference bridges the gap between the sample we can measure and the population we want to understand.</p></div>

<h2>6.2 The P-Value and Statistical Significance</h2>
<p>The core mechanism of inferential statistics is hypothesis testing, which produces the famous-and frequently misunderstood-<strong>p-value</strong>. The p-value answers a very specific, slightly counterintuitive question: If the null hypothesis were true (i.e., if there were truly no effect or no difference in the population), what is the probability of getting a result as large as the one observed in the sample just by chance? (Cohen, 1994).</p>
<p>If the p-value is very small (conventionally, less than 0.05, or 5%), it means that your result would be highly unlikely to occur by chance if there were truly no effect in the population. Because it is so unlikely, researchers reject the null hypothesis and declare the result <strong>statistically significant</strong>. A p-value of 0.03 means there is a 3% probability of obtaining these results by chance if the null hypothesis is true. A p-value greater than 0.05 means there is too high a probability that the result is just random noise, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>A critical warning: a p-value is <em>not</em> the probability that your hypothesis is right. It is also <em>not</em> a measure of how important or large the effect is. A very small p-value (e.g., p = 0.001) simply means you are very confident that an effect exists; it doesn't mean the effect is massive. With a sample size of 10,000 people, even a microscopic, meaningless difference between groups will be highly statistically significant (Wasserstein and Lazar, 2016).</p>

<h2>6.3 Type I and Type II Errors</h2>
<p>Because inference relies on probability, it is never perfectly certain. Researchers can make two types of errors when interpreting statistical significance. A <strong>Type I Error (False Positive)</strong> occurs when the researcher concludes there is an effect, but in reality, there is not. This is equivalent to convicting an innocent person. The probability of making a Type I error is determined by your significance level (alpha), which is why we set it low, typically at 0.05 (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>A <strong>Type II Error (False Negative)</strong> occurs when there truly is an effect in the population, but the study fails to detect it (finding a non-significant p-value). This is equivalent to letting a guilty person go free. Type II errors are usually caused by a sample size that is too small, which results in low statistical power. The study lacks the mathematical muscle to detect the effect (Cohen, 1992).</p>

<h2>6.4 Moving Beyond P-Values: Effect Size and Confidence Intervals</h2>
<p>In recent years, the scientific community has heavily criticised the over-reliance on p-values (Wasserstein and Lazar, 2016). To present a complete picture, inferential statistics must include two other metrics. </p>
<p><strong>Effect size</strong> measures the magnitude or practical importance of the result. While a p-value tells you if an effect exists, the effect size tells you if the effect is large enough to care about. Common effect size metrics include Cohen's <em>d</em> for differences between groups and Pearson's <em>r</em> for relationships (Field, 2018).</p>
<p><strong>Confidence Intervals (CI)</strong> provide a range of values within which the true population parameter is likely to fall. A 95% confidence interval means that if you repeated the study 100 times, 95 of those calculated intervals would contain the true population mean. CIs are much more informative than a simple p-value because they show the precision of your estimate (Cumming, 2014).</p>`;
}

function ch07() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 7</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Hypothesis Testing: t-Tests, ANOVA, and Chi-Square Explained</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Understand when to use t-tests to compare two groups<br>• Distinguish between independent and paired samples t-tests<br>• Understand when to use Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) for three or more groups<br>• Explain the purpose of post-hoc tests in ANOVA<br>• Apply the Chi-Square test for categorical data analysis</blockquote><h2>7.1 Comparing Groups: The Independent t-Test</h2>
<p>The most common scenario in experimental and quasi-experimental research involves comparing two groups on a continuous outcome variable. For example, you might want to know if students who receive a new tutoring method (Group 1) score higher on a math test than students who receive traditional teaching (Group 2). The statistical tool for this job is the <strong>Independent-Samples t-test</strong> (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The t-test works by comparing the difference between the two group means against the natural variability (standard deviation) within the groups. If the difference between the means is large, and the variability within the groups is small, the t-test produces a large t-statistic and a small p-value, indicating that the groups are genuinely different. The test requires an independent categorical variable with exactly two levels, and a continuous dependent variable. It assumes that the data is normally distributed and that both groups have roughly equal variances (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<h2>7.2 Comparing the Same Group Twice: The Paired t-Test</h2>
<p>Sometimes you don't have two different groups; you have one group measured at two different times. A classic example is a pre-test/post-test design: you measure anxiety levels before an intervention, deliver the intervention, and measure anxiety again in the exact same people. In this case, you use a <strong>Paired-Samples (or Dependent) t-test</strong> (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>Because the same people are tested twice, their scores are linked. The paired t-test capitalises on this by looking at the difference score for each individual, rather than just comparing the overall means. This makes it a very powerful test, as it controls for individual differences (e.g., people who are naturally more anxious will likely have higher scores on both tests, which the paired t-test accounts for) (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Which Test Do I Need? (Comparing Groups)</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-3"><div class="diagram-box"><h4>Independent t-Test</h4><p><strong>Use when:</strong> Comparing 2 different groups.<br><strong>Example:</strong> Male vs. Female salaries.<br><strong>Variables:</strong> 1 Categorical (2 levels), 1 Continuous.</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--gold);"><h4>Paired t-Test</h4><p><strong>Use when:</strong> Comparing same group twice.<br><strong>Example:</strong> Pre-test vs. Post-test scores.<br><strong>Variables:</strong> Same continuous variable measured at Time 1 and Time 2.</p></div><div class="diagram-box" style="border-top-color:var(--teal);"><h4>One-Way ANOVA</h4><p><strong>Use when:</strong> Comparing 3+ different groups.<br><strong>Example:</strong> Therapy A vs. Therapy B vs. Control.<br><strong>Variables:</strong> 1 Categorical (3+ levels), 1 Continuous.</p></div></div></div>

<h2>7.3 Comparing Three or More Groups: ANOVA</h2>
<p>What happens if you have three groups? Perhaps you are testing three different diets. You might be tempted to run three separate t-tests (Diet A vs B, A vs C, B vs C). This is a statistical sin. Every time you run a test, there is a 5% chance of making a Type I error (a false positive). If you run multiple tests on the same data, those chances accumulate, drastically inflating your risk of declaring a significant result that isn't real (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The solution is <strong>Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)</strong>. ANOVA allows you to compare three or more groups in a single test, keeping the error rate strictly at 5%. The output of an ANOVA is an F-statistic. If the F-statistic is significant (p < 0.05), it tells you that there is a significant difference somewhere among the groups. However, it does not tell you <em>which</em> groups are different. To find out exactly where the differences lie, you must conduct <strong>post-hoc tests</strong> (such as Tukey or Bonferroni tests), which are special follow-up tests designed to compare specific groups while controlling for the error rate (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<h2>7.4 Categorical Data: The Chi-Square Test</h2>
<p>The t-tests and ANOVA all require the dependent variable to be continuous (interval or ratio data). But what if both your independent and dependent variables are categorical (nominal data)? For example, you want to know if there is an association between gender (Male/Female) and voting preference (Candidate A/Candidate B). You cannot calculate means for these variables.</p>
<p>In this scenario, you use the <strong>Chi-Square Test for Independence</strong>. This test is based on frequencies and cross-tabulations. It calculates the frequencies you would <em>expect</em> to see in each category if there were no relationship, and compares them to the frequencies you <em>actually observed</em> in your data. If the observed frequencies deviate significantly from the expected frequencies, the Chi-Square test returns a significant p-value, indicating that the two categorical variables are associated (Field, 2018).</p>`;
}

function ch08() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 8</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Correlation and Regression Analysis</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Explain the concept of correlation and interpret a correlation coefficient (r)<br>• Distinguish between correlation and causation<br>• Understand the purpose and mechanics of simple linear regression<br>• Explain how multiple regression accommodates several predictor variables<br>• Interpret R-squared as a measure of explained variance</blockquote><h2>8.1 Exploring Relationships: Correlation</h2>
<p>While t-tests and ANOVAs look for differences between distinct groups, correlation and regression look for relationships between continuous variables. If a researcher wants to know whether time spent studying is related to exam scores, they use correlation. The most common metric is the <strong>Pearson correlation coefficient (r)</strong>, which measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two continuous variables (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The correlation coefficient ranges from -1.0 to +1.0. The sign (+ or -) indicates the <em>direction</em>. A positive correlation means that as one variable goes up, the other goes up (e.g., height and weight). A negative correlation means that as one variable goes up, the other goes down (e.g., alcohol consumption and reaction speed). The number itself indicates the <em>strength</em>. A value of 0 means there is no linear relationship. Values close to 1 (or -1) indicate a very strong, tight relationship. By convention, 0.1 is weak, 0.3 is moderate, and 0.5 is strong (Cohen, 1992).</p>
<p>It is mandatory here to repeat the oldest mantra in statistics: <strong>Correlation does not imply causation</strong>. A strong positive correlation between ice cream sales and shark attacks does not mean ice cream attracts sharks; both are caused by a third, unmeasured variable (summer weather). Correlation only proves that two variables move together in a mathematical sense (Pallant, 2020).</p>

<div style="margin:22px 0;text-align:center;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 540 240" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;"><text x="270" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#1a2332" font-size="14" font-weight="700" font-family="Inter,sans-serif">UNDERSTANDING THE CORRELATION COEFFICIENT (r)</text><rect x="20" y="55" width="500" height="15" rx="7.5" fill="#f0f4f8" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="1"/><rect x="20" y="55" width="250" height="15" fill="url(#gradNegative)"/><rect x="270" y="55" width="250" height="15" fill="url(#gradPositive)"/><circle cx="20" cy="62.5" r="4" fill="#8b3a3a"/><text x="20" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b3a3a" font-size="10" font-weight="700">-1.0</text><text x="20" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Perfect</text><text x="20" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Negative</text><circle cx="145" cy="62.5" r="4" fill="#cf6a4f"/><text x="145" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="#cf6a4f" font-size="10" font-weight="700">-0.5</text><text x="145" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Moderate</text><text x="145" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Negative</text><circle cx="270" cy="62.5" r="4" fill="#666"/><text x="270" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="10" font-weight="700">0</text><text x="270" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">No Linear</text><text x="270" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Relationship</text><circle cx="395" cy="62.5" r="4" fill="#6ab085"/><text x="395" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="#2d6a4f" font-size="10" font-weight="700">+0.5</text><text x="395" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Moderate</text><text x="395" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Positive</text><circle cx="520" cy="62.5" r="4" fill="#2d6a4f"/><text x="520" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="#2d6a4f" font-size="10" font-weight="700">+1.0</text><text x="520" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Perfect</text><text x="520" y="112" text-anchor="middle" fill="#666" font-size="9">Positive</text><rect x="60" y="150" width="420" height="70" rx="8" fill="#1a3a5c"/><text x="270" y="175" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c9a227" font-size="11" font-weight="700">CRITICAL DISTINCTION</text><text x="270" y="195" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10">SIGN (+ or -) indicates DIRECTION.</text><text x="270" y="210" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-size="10">NUMBER (0 to 1) indicates STRENGTH.</text><defs><linearGradient id="gradNegative" x1="0%" y1="0%" x2="100%" y2="0%"><stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#8b3a3a;stop-opacity:1"/><stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#f0f4f8;stop-opacity:1"/></linearGradient><linearGradient id="gradPositive" x1="0%" y1="0%" x2="100%" y2="0%"><stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#f0f4f8;stop-opacity:1"/><stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#2d6a4f;stop-opacity:1"/></linearGradient></defs></svg><p style="font-style:italic;color:#666;font-size:.8rem;margin-top:8px;text-align:center;">Figure 8.1 The correlation coefficient (r) measures both the strength and direction of a relationship.</p></div>

<h2>8.2 Prediction: Simple Linear Regression</h2>
<p>While correlation tells you that two variables are related, it does not allow you to make predictions. If you want to use someone's score on Variable A to predict their score on Variable B, you need regression. <strong>Simple Linear Regression</strong> takes the correlational relationship and fits a mathematical line (the line of best fit) through the data points. This allows the researcher to establish an independent (predictor) variable and a dependent (outcome) variable (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The output of a regression provides an equation (Y = bX + a). It tells you exactly how much the dependent variable (Y) will change for every one-unit increase in the independent variable (X). If you run a regression predicting salary based on years of education, the regression coefficient (b) might tell you that for every additional year of education, salary increases by $5,000. This provides immense practical utility (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>

<h2>8.3 Multiple Regression</h2>
<p>Human behaviour is rarely determined by a single factor. Salary isn't just predicted by education; it is also predicted by years of experience, industry, and geographic location. <strong>Multiple Regression</strong> allows a researcher to include several independent predictor variables in the same model to predict a single continuous dependent variable (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>The true power of multiple regression lies in its ability to isolate variables. It tells you the predictive power of Variable A <em>while holding Variables B and C constant</em>. This helps solve the problem of confounding variables. If you want to know if gender impacts salary, you must put education and experience into the multiple regression model as well. If gender is still a significant predictor after controlling for experience and education, you have much stronger evidence of a gender pay gap (Field, 2018).</p>
<p>The most important overarching metric produced by any regression model is <strong>R-squared (R²)</strong>. This represents the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variables in the model. If your model predicting salary has an R² of 0.40, it means that your predictors explain 40% of the reasons why salaries differ among people; the remaining 60% is due to factors not included in your model. In the social sciences, an R² of 0.30 or 0.40 is often considered quite good, as human behaviour is highly complex (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2019).</p>`;
}

function ch09() {
  return `<h1>Chapter 9</h1><h2 style='font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:4px;'>Reading and Reporting Statistical Output Correctly</h2><blockquote><strong>Learning Objectives</strong><br>By the end of this chapter, you will be able to:<br>• Extract the necessary information from complex statistical software outputs<br>• Report statistical results according to APA style guidelines<br>• Distinguish between statistical significance and practical significance<br>• Avoid common errors in interpreting p-values and confidence intervals<br>• Write clear, narrative interpretations of numerical results for a general audience</blockquote><h2>9.1 Surviving the Output Dump</h2>
<p>One of the most intimidating experiences for a novice researcher is running a statistical test in software like SPSS or R and being confronted with the output. A simple t-test can generate three tables filled with dozens of numbers, acronyms (df, Sig., F, t), and confidence intervals. The skill required here is filtering: knowing exactly which numbers matter and which can be safely ignored. Software generates everything possible; the researcher must extract only what is relevant (Pallant, 2020).</p>
<p>For any inferential test, you generally need to extract three core components: the descriptive statistics (means and standard deviations for the groups), the test statistic and its degrees of freedom (e.g., the t-value or F-value, which proves you ran the test), and the significance level (the p-value). Increasingly, journals also demand a fourth component: the effect size (Field, 2018).</p>

<div class="diagram-container"><div class="diagram-header">Anatomy of an APA Statistical Sentence</div><div class="diagram-grid grid-1"><div class="diagram-box" style="text-align:left; padding:20px;"><h4>The Formula:</h4><p style="font-family:monospace; background:#f4f4f4; padding:10px; border-radius:4px;">[Narrative claim], test(df) = [statistic], p = [value], effect size = [value].</p><h4>Example (Independent t-test):</h4><p style="font-family:serif; font-size:1.1rem;">"Students in the tutoring group scored significantly higher on the exam (<em>M</em> = 85.4, <em>SD</em> = 6.2) than students in the control group (<em>M</em> = 72.1, <em>SD</em> = 8.4), <em>t</em>(98) = 4.32, <em>p</em> < .001, <em>d</em> = 0.82."</p><h4 style="margin-top:15px;">Breakdown:</h4><ul style="margin-top:5px;"><li><strong>Descriptives:</strong> (<em>M</em> = 85.4, <em>SD</em> = 6.2) tells the reader the actual scores.</li><li><strong>Test Statistic & DF:</strong> <em>t</em>(98) = 4.32 proves the test was run and shows sample size context.</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> <em>p</em> < .001 proves the difference is statistically real, not chance.</li><li><strong>Effect Size:</strong> <em>d</em> = 0.82 proves the difference is large and practically meaningful.</li></ul></div></div></div>

<h2>9.2 The Rules of Reporting (APA Style)</h2>
<p>The American Psychological Association (APA) style is the standard for reporting statistics across most social and behavioural sciences. Adhering strictly to these formatting rules is a hallmark of professional research writing. Some key rules include: statistical symbols (like <em>t</em>, <em>F</em>, <em>p</em>, <em>M</em>, <em>SD</em>) are always italicised. Exact p-values should be reported (e.g., <em>p</em> = .034) rather than just stating <em>p</em> < .05, unless the value is less than .001, which is reported as <em>p</em> < .001. Leading zeros are omitted for statistics that cannot exceed 1.0 (like p-values and correlations), so write .034, not 0.034 (American Psychological Association, 2020).</p>
<p>When reporting results, the text must tell a coherent story. Do not simply list statistics. The narrative text should state the finding in plain English, and the statistics should be provided in parentheses to support the claim. The reader should be able to understand the conclusion even if they skip over the numbers entirely (Field, 2018).</p>

<h2>9.3 Practical vs. Statistical Significance</h2>
<p>The most common interpretive error in quantitative research is confusing statistical significance with practical significance. If you have a massive dataset of 50,000 people, an intervention that increases test scores by 0.5 points out of 100 will likely yield a p-value of < .001. It is highly statistically significant; you are mathematically certain the 0.5 point difference is real. But practically, a 0.5 point difference is useless. It has no real-world impact (Wasserstein and Lazar, 2016).</p>
<p>This is why effect sizes must be reported and interpreted. When discussing your findings, you must explicitly state whether the effect is large enough to matter in the real world. A researcher who boasts about a highly significant p-value while hiding a microscopic effect size is either demonstrating statistical ignorance or engaging in academic dishonesty. Honest reporting requires presenting the p-value to prove the effect exists, and the effect size to prove it matters (Cumming, 2014).</p>`;
}

module.exports = { ch01, ch02, ch03, ch04, ch05, ch06, ch07, ch08, ch09 };
